sentences: Reina Ueda (上田 麗奈, Ueda Reina, born January 17, 1994) is a Japanese voice actress and singer from Toyama Prefecture.
Beginning her career as a voice actress in 2012, her first main role was Naru Sekiya, the protagonist of the 2014 anime series Hanayamata.

She was one of the recipients of the Best New Actress Award in the 9th Seiyu Awards in 2015.

Ueda was born in Toyama Prefecture on January 17, 1994.
During her third year of high school, she applied for a voice acting audition only three days before the deadline of it.

Ueda won the Second Class Grand Prix in an audition held by the agency 81 Produce in 2011, and formally joined the agency the following year.
Ueda won the Second Class Grand Prix in an audition held by the agency 81 Produce in 2011, and formally joined the agency the following year.
In 2013, she voiced 18 sisters in the anime series Tesagure!

In 2014, Ueda was cast in her first main role as Naru Sekiya, the protagonist of the anime series Hanayamata; she and her co-stars performed the series' opening theme "Hana wa Odoreya Iroha ni Ho" (花ハ踊レヤいろはにほ, Dancing in the Scent of Flowers) under the name Team Hanayamata.
The following year, she was cast as Meika Katai in Mikagura School Suite, Mikan Akemi in My Monster Secret, and Elena Arshavina in World Break: Aria of Curse for a Holy Swordsman.
In 2016, Ueda played the role of Hane Sakura, the protagonist of the anime series Bakuon!!
, Mira Yurisaki in Dimension W, Sophie Noelle in Kuromukuro, and Mallow in Pokémon: Sun & Moon.
That same year, she made her debut as a singer, releasing the mini-album RefRain on December 21.

In 2017, Ueda played the roles of Hiromi Maiharu in Minami Kamakura High School
She also made an appearance at New Jersey's AnimeNEXT event in April.
In 2018, she played the roles of Arthur Pendragon in Märchen Mädchen and Akane Shinjō in SSSS.
She also released her first solo single "Sleepland" on February 7, 2018; the title track is used as the ending theme to Märchen Mädchen.
In 2019, she was cast as Miyako Hoshino in Wataten!:
In 2020, she voiced Shuka Karino in Darwin's Game.
She also released her second single "Literature" (リテラチュア) on October 21, 2020; the title track was used as the opening theme to the anime series Wandering Witch: The Journey of Elaina.
